e\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2532438\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Okt 13, 2022</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104tnn1665702954367.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/tnn1665702954367.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/tnn1665702954367.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"tnn1665702954367\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Environment Considerations for Oracle\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body refbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">\n</p>\n<section class=\"section\">\n<p class=\"p\"></p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d713365e59\">\n                        \n Network Considerations\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55145e1_d55146e1_d55147e1\">You can use either the Uniface Application Server or SQL*Net for network connectivity.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55148e1_d55149e1_d55150e1\">If you use SQL*Net, you must consider the following points to avoid problems arising from different data representations on machines with different architectures:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25412e1_d25413e1_d25414e1\">Install Uniface with a system-independent byte sequence.\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25415e1_d25416e1_d25417e1\">It is recommended that you define the Oracle client character set. It is possible that the default character set defined in your Oracle client environment is different from the database to which your application connects. In this case, the character set in your Oracle client environment should be set to <code class=\"ph codeph\">NLS_LANG</code>.\n </li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55151e1_d55152e1_d55153e1\">For example, you should use the <code class=\"ph codeph\">NLS_LANG</code> environment variable whenever the database to which your application connects uses a different character set than the default set defined in your Oracle client environment.</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d713365e89\">\n                        \n Permissions\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55157e1_d55158e1_d55159e1\">When developing a Uniface application with an Oracle database, the developer must have the privileges to connect to the database, to create tables and to create procedures. These privileges are necessary both when schema objects are created on the fly, and when scripts generated by the Create Table facility are executed.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55160e1_d55161e1_d55162e1\">The database administrator should create a <code class=\"ph codeph\">UNIFACE_DEVELOPER</code> role, which is granted to all users working with the Uniface IDE. It is recommended that the following privileges be granted to the <code class=\"ph codeph\">UNIFACE_DEVELOPER</code> role:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25418e1_d25419e1_d25420e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE VIEW</code>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25421e1_d25422e1_d25423e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE SEQUENCE</code>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25424e1_d25425e1_d25426e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">ALTER SESSION</code>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25427e1_d25428e1_d25429e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE TRIGGER</code>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25430e1_d25431e1_d25432e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE DATABASE LINK</code>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__li_d25433e1_d25434e1_d25435e1\">\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE Records, indexes, tables, and fields</code>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55163e1_d55164e1_d55165e1\">For example:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">CREATE ROLE UNIFACE_DEVELOPER;\nGRANT CREATE SESSION, CREATE TABLE,\nCREATE PROCEDURE TO UNIFACE_DEVELOPER;\nGRANT UNIFACE_DEVELOPER TO <var class=\"keyword varname\">UserName</var>,\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">UserName</var>,...,<var class=\"keyword varname\">UserNameN</var>;\n</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"tnn1665702954367__p_d55166e1_d55167e1_d55168e1\">Once modeling is complete, and all tables and packages have been created, the <code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE TABLE</code> and <code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE PROCEDURE</code> privileges are no longer required. If the Oracle RDBMS does not have the Procedural option, or the <code class=\"ph codeph\">disable packages</code> connector option is set, the <code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE PROCEDURE</code> privilege is not required. It is, however, recommended.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2532438\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2532438\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Environment Considerations for Oracle Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 13, 2022 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Environment Considerations for Oracle Network Considerations You can use either the Uniface Application Server or SQL*Net for network connectivity. If you use SQL*Net, you must consider the following points to avoid problems arising from different data representations on machines with different architectures: Install Uniface with a system-independent byte sequence. It is recommended that you define the Oracle client character set. It is possible that the default character set defined in your Oracle client environment is different from the database to which your application connects. In this case, the character set in your Oracle client environment should be set to NLS_LANG . For example, you should use the NLS_LANG environment variable whenever the database to which your application connects uses a different character set than the default set defined in your Oracle client environment. Permissions When developing a Uniface application with an Oracle database, the developer must have the privileges to connect to the database, to create tables and to create procedures. These privileges are necessary both when schema objects are created on the fly, and when scripts generated by the Create Table facility are executed. The database administrator should create a UNIFACE_DEVELOPER role, which is granted to all users working with the Uniface IDE. It is recommended that the following privileges be granted to the UNIFACE_DEVELOPER role: CREATE VIEW CREATE SEQUENCE ALTER SESSION CREATE TRIGGER CREATE DATABASE LINK CREATE Records, indexes, tables, and fields For example: CREATE ROLE UNIFACE_DEVELOPER; GRANT CREATE SESSION, CREATE TABLE, CREATE PROCEDURE TO UNIFACE_DEVELOPER; GRANT UNIFACE_DEVELOPER TO UserName , UserName ,..., UserNameN ; Copy Once modeling is complete, and all tables and packages have been created, the CREATE TABLE and CREATE PROCEDURE privileges are no longer required. If the Oracle RDBMS does not have the Procedural option, or the disable packages connector option is set, the CREATE PROCEDURE privilege is not required. It is, however, recommended. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}